definition.value: An oligonucleotide comprising five deoxythymidylic acid residues linked 5'->3'.

A benzamide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-aminobenzoic acid with the primary amino group of 1-(2-aminoethyl)-2-cyano-3-{3-[3-(piperidin-1-ylmethyl)phenoxy]propyl}guanidine.
An oligonucleotide comprising ten deoxythymidylic acid residues linked 5'->3'.
An oligonucleotide comprising fifteen deoxythymidylic acid residues linked 5'->3'.
An oligonucleotide comprising twenty deoxythymidylic acid residues linked 5'->3'.
An aminobenzoic acid that is anthranilic acid substituted at position 5 by a (1-methoxy-2-methylindolizin-3-yl)carbonyl group.
An aminobenzoate that is the conjugate base of 2-amino-5-[(1-methoxy-2-methylindolizin-3-yl)carbonyl]benzoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion ontained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any aromatic 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid; major species at pH 7.3. In the structure shown R is an aromatic group.
An agonist at the A2A receptor.
An agonist at any adenosine receptor.
A tripeptide composed of three L-alanine units joined by peptide linkages.
A tetrapeptide composed of two L-alanine units linked to two L-aspartic acid units by peptide linkages.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any 1-alkylglycerone 3-phosphate.
An organophosphate oxoanion formed by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of any 2'-deoxynucleoside 5'-diphosphate.
A tripeptide composed of two L-alanyl and an L-aspartic acid residue joined in sequence.
A tripeptide composed of two L-alanine units and a glycine joined by peptide linkages.
An agonist at the adenosine A3 receptor.
A 1-alkyl-2-acyl-sn-glycerol in which the 1-alkyl substituent can be any alk-1-enyl group.
A tripeptide composed of two L-alanyl units and an L-serine joined by peptide linkages.
Any 1-(alk-1-enyl)glycerol having 2S-configuration.
A tripeptide composed of two L-alanyl units and an L-proline joined by peptide linkages.
A tetrapeptide composed of two L-alanine units joined to two L-proline units by peptide linkages.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any 1-(alk-1-enyl)-sn-glycero-3-phosphate.
A tetrapeptide composed of an L-alanyl, two L-asparagyl units, and an L-proline joined by peptide linkages.
A 1-alkyl-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate(2-) in which the 1-alkyl substituent can be any alk-1-enyl group. Major species at pH 7.3.
A tetrapeptide composed of L-alanyl, L-asparagyl, L-aspartyl, and L-proline residues joined in sequence.
A dipeptide composed of L-alanine and L-asparagine units joined by a peptide linkage.
A tetrapeptide composed of L-alanyl, L-asparagyl, L-glutamyl, and L-serine residues joined in sequence.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any 1-alkyl-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate.
An acaricide that kills mites of the genus Sarcoptes.
A hormone agonist that binds to and activates a thyroid hormone receptor.
A photochemical role realized in the absorption of ultraviolet light, for example to protect skin cells from damage.
A drug used in treating and healing of wounds.
An aralkylamino compound that is histamine bearing a methyl substituent at the alpha-position (the R-enantiomer).
A pyridobenzodiazepine that acts as a selective antagonist of the muscarinic acetylcholine receptors.
A tetramine that is N,N'-bis(6-aminohexyl)octane-1,8-diamine where the primary amino groups both carry 2-methoxybenzyl substituents.
A quaternary ammonium salt obtained by combining equimolar amounts of 4-diphenylacetoxy-N-methylpiperidine and iodomethane.
A tripeptide composed of L-alanine, L-aspartic acid, and glycine units joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-alanine, L-aspartic acid, and L-proline units joined in sequernce by peptide linkages.
A phenylpropanoid that is phenol substituted at position 4 by a prop-1-enyl group (the trans-isomer)
A tripeptide composed of L-alanine, L-aspartic acid, and L-serine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-alanine, L-cysteine, and glycine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A phenylpropanoid that is trans-p-coumaryl alcohol in which the hydrogen from the allylic hydroxy group is replaced by an acetyl group.
A tripeptide composed of L-alanine, L-glutamine, and L-proline joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-alanine, glycine, and L-histidine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-alanine, glycine, and L-proline joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-alanine, glycine, L-serine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-alanine, glycine, and L-tyrosine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
Any agent used to determine the amino-acid sequence in a polypeptide.
A tetrapeptide composed of L-alanine, L-leucine, L-alanine, and L-proline joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
